As well as his work in the dairying sector, Waite soon became involved in local politics and joined the [[New Zealand Reform Party|Reform Party]].<ref name=Green/> He first stood for election to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in {{NZ election link year|1925}}, when he defeated the incumbent in the {{NZ electorate link|Clutha}} electorate, [[John Edie (New Zealand politician)|John Edie]] of the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]], with ease.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=145}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Reform Triumph |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NA19251105.2.46 |accessdate=25 November 2013 |newspaper=[[The Northern Advocate]] |date=5 November 1925 |page=6}}</ref> He was one of 13 new members in a House of 80 representatives.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Members |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=OSWCC19251110.2.43 |accessdate=26 November 2013 |newspaper=Otautau Standard and Wallace County Chronicle |volume=XXI |issue=1055 |date=10 November 1925 |page=6}}</ref> In the {{NZ election link|1928}}, he was challenged by Joseph Stephens,<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour's Candidates |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=MW19221122.2.11 |accessdate=26 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Maoriland Worker]] |date=22 November 1922 |volume=12 |issue=299 |page=12}}</ref> who was an [[Independent politician|independent]] candidate describing himself as [[Liberal-Labour (New Zealand)|Liberal-Labour]]. Waite had a 523-vote margin, which represented 6.5% of the valid votes.<ref>{{cite book |title=The General Election, 1928 |year=1929 |publisher=Government Printer |url= http://atojs.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/atojs?a=d&cl=search&d=AJHR1929-I.2.3.2.37 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> In the {{NZ election link|1931}}, Waite was defeated by [[Peter McSkimming]], who stood as an Independent, but had links to the [[United Party (New Zealand)|United Party]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=145}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Elections Recounts |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19311212.2.81 |accessdate=29 January 2014 |newspaper=[[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]] |date=12 December 1931 |volume=CXII |issue=142 |page=10}}</ref>

Prime Minister [[George Forbes (New Zealand politician)|George Forbes]] had not made appointments to the [[New Zealand Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] since 1930, with the exception of [[James Parr (politician)|James Parr]] in 1931, and membership dwindled during the years of the [[Great Depression]]. By 1934, the membership had reduced to 19, the lowest since 1860, with two members about to retire. In 1934, 14 new members were appointed by Forbes, including Waite.{{sfn|Jackson|1972|p=68}} All appointments became effective on 22 June 1934,{{sfn|Wilson|1985|pp=148–166}} and Waite, at age 49, was the second youngest of the intake; only [[Vincent Ward (politician)|Vincent Ward]] was younger.{{sfn|Jackson|1972|p=230}} Waite was reappointed twice, and served until the [[Suicide squad (New Zealand)|abolition of the Upper House]] in 1950.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=166}}

When the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] was formed in 1936 from the merger of Reform and the [[United Party (New Zealand)|United Party]], publicity was one of the major considerations. The party's provisional council established a sub-committee consisting of [[Henry Livingstone]], [[Frederick Doidge]], and Waite. This committee reported back in February 1937, recommending the establishment of a Dominion publicity committee, and a trustee company for the purpose of publishing a party newsletter. Party Publications Ltd was thus created, and Waite was the first editor of ''The National News''. Initially, all financial members were to receive this monthly newsletter, aimed at being a counterpart to [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour]]'s ''Standard''.{{sfn|Gustafson|1986|p=195}} While ''The National News'' performed an important function during the party's formative years, the venture was expensive and following the {{NZ election link|1938}}, it was changed to a quarterly schedule, before being discontinued in September 1939 just after the outbreak of the war.{{sfn|Gustafson|1986|p=196}}

The seven-member Dominion publicity committee, of which Waite was a member, engaged three advertising companies to jointly prepare for the 1938 election. Two of those companies, John Ilott and Charles Haines,<ref>{{cite web |last=Phillips |first=Jock |title=Advertising – Advertising agencies, 1891–1970 |url= http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/advertising/page-2 |publisher=[[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] |accessdate=26 January 2014 |authorlink=Jock Phillips |date=13 July 2012}}</ref> remained joint agents for the National Party until 1973.{{sfn|Gustafson|1986|p=196}}

==Second World War==
[[File:LC Waite with Prime Minister Fraser, 1941.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Colonel Waite (far right) with Prime Minister [[Peter Fraser (New Zealand politician)|Peter Fraser]] (in white suit), visiting the Infantry Training Depot at Maadi Camp in Egypt, May 1941]]
When the [[Second World War]] began, Waite was still a lieutenant colonel in the TF. He was appointed overseas commissioner for the National Patriotic Fund Board. Based in Egypt, he worked to provide the soldiers of the Second New Zealand Expeditionary Force with special supplies and treats.<ref name=Green/> His services in this capacity were recognised in 1944 with his appointment as an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=36493 |date=2 May 1944 |startpage=2005 |supp=yes |accessdate=25 November 2013}}</ref> He finished the war a [[colonel]], working in Europe on the repatriation of New Zealand personnel recently released from prisoner-of-war camps in Germany. In 1946, he travelled to Japan to inspect the infrastructure set up for [[J Force|J-Force]], New Zealand's contribution to the [[British Commonwealth Occupation Force]], following which he retired from the military. In the [[1946 Birthday Honours|1946 King's Birthday Honours]], he was appointed a [[Order of St Michael and St George|Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]].<ref name=Green/><ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 37601 |date=4 June 1946 |startpage=2835 |supp=yes |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>

==Later life==
In his retirement, Waite wrote papers on archeology and history including one on Egyptian pottery. While in [[Cairo]] during the Second World War, he collected several historical antiquities on behalf of the [[Otago Museum]].<ref name=Green/> In 1951 Waite was granted the right to retain the title of "Honourable", having served more than 10 years as a member of the Legislative Council.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39156 |date=23 February 1951 |startpage=977 |accessdate=25 November 2013}}</ref> In his later years, his health was poor and he died in Balclutha in 1952 at the age of 67. He was survived by his wife and a daughter.<ref name=Green/>

